    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Religion is back in the political news, this time in Louisiana.</p>
        <p>A lengthy drought there has parched fields and forests that usually are all but awash in water, killing crops and leaving piney woodlands ready to explode in fire. So 10 days ago, Gov. Mike Foster issued an official proclamation asking Louisianans to pray for rain.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Religion is back in the political news, this time in Louisiana.</p>
        <p>A lengthy drought there has parched fields and forests that usually are all but awash in water, killing crops and leaving piney woodlands ready to explode in fire. So 10 days ago, Gov. Mike Foster issued an official proclamation asking Louisianans to pray for rain.</p>
        <p>That was too much for Joe Cook of the Louisiana chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union.</p>
        <p>Mr. Cook told The Advocate of Baton Rouge that the governor, a Republican, had crossed the constitutional line that separates church and state.</p>
        <p>Mr. Foster countered that elected leaders all over the United States often called for prayers in times of disaster and hardship. Mr. Cook, he suggested, should ''get a life.''</p>
        <p>On Thursday, some sprinkles fell.</p>
        <p>Did the prayers work?</p>
        <p>''Rained today, didn't it?'' the governor replied.</p>
      </block>
